“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, blocked, hopes that the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Sailors patrol an armoured boat at La Paz Naval Headquarters.
Public buildings carry a blue flag like the ocean.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases display the following motorcycle: “The sea is rightfully ours.
Recovering it is a duty.”
Across blocked Bolivia, the memory of a lost coast to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still very much present, as is the desire to sail on the Pacific Ocean once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades, since Bolivia is awaiting a decision by the International Court of Justice, which will be rendered on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive result,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on the big screen throughout the country, hoping that the Hague court will vote in favor of the Bolivian claim. Bolivia hopes that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile will be obliged to negotiate the agreement of a sovereign ocean crossing to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia (who is facing a controversial fight for re-election next year), also has a lot to say about the decision that will be made Monday.
“We are so close to being able to return to the Pacific Ocean,” he said in late August.
But some analysts believe that there is little chance that the court will rule in favor of Chile, and that little would change, even in the event of a positive decision.
The Netherlands-based UN body does not have the power to grant Chilean territory, and stipulated that it would not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice made its decision six months after the last arguments shows that the case “was not complicated,” says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And far from favoring the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may have even harmed it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been diverted by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morales’s warlike rhetoric undermined all the remaining Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange, but after that it will be very difficult to hold talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the Court’s decision-making was abnormally fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also disputed the fact that Morales – who remains to this day one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – used the maritime problem as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The court’s decision is an opportunity to see that we need to get rid of the past.”
