John Edward: Language skills are essential to the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence. This trend continued in 2018 with excellent new exam results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the highest level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, the career they have chosen and in their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector able to design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that contemporary languages remain popular and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, you speak to his heart.”
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to build relationships and build trust with people in other countries.
If we look at the excellent exam results this year, we find that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages scored the highest, A.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, show that 72% of students scored the highest, A, in Mandarin, as did the 72% of students who studied German, the 69% of students who studied French and the 63% of students who studied Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and youth in the future.
Languages as subjects are now organized as are science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that among the difficulties employers face in recruiting candidates, 17% are linked to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
Regardless of your career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real advantage in the future thanks to this long-lasting skill.
Being able to communicate directly with strangers will automatically place the multilingual person in front of their competitors.
According to a YouGov survey conducted in 2013 of 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% of them did not speak a foreign language sufficiently to hold a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, especially those in emerging economies, children will have better chances of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Many of them will focus on contemporary classical languages, while others will teach languages considered important to the UK in the run-up to 2020, including Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s preferences, several languages will be accessible in independent schools, with specialized staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It is clear that at present, in a global business environment, languages remain of paramount importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
