Almanach: The Inventor of the Geiger Meter
And now a page from our Almanac "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and THE TOURNING ACCOUNT... was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity; an invention that subsequently gave rise to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A pillar of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become fundamental in pop culture, as can be seen in the 1950 film “Bells of Coronado,” with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, two unlikely scientists:
A man: “What is this?”
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, we use it to look for radioactive minerals, like uranium.
With these headphones, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms released into the minerals by radioactivity.”
Evans: “Say, it’s definitely going to jump!”
“Hans” Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains.
