Solid allows users to choose where their data is saved as well as the persons authorized to access such or such information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt was aimed at “dominating the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said of the launch.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology to allow people to create their own “online personal data store” or DPL.
It can contain contact lists, task lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available at the same time on a single browser.
The particularity of the online personal data store is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access what type of information.
The company calls this “personal responsibility through data.”
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, Inrupt’s idea is that the company brings the right resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a few developers working on contract on the project, and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to build their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not yet in discussion with “Facebook and Google” about whether or not to make a complete change where all their business models are completely changed in an instant.
“We don’t ask their permission.”
In an article on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that [Inrupt’s] mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem in order to protect the integrity and quality of the new web built on Solid.
In 1994, at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating the World Wide Web Consortium.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the net neutrality debate.
Although he launched Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely optimistic about this new era of the web,” Berners-Lee added.
