Olympic diver Tom Daley claims to have grown up feeling inferior to others because of his sexuality – but that gave him the motivation to succeed.
The 24-year-old said he didn’t realize until he went to high school that “not everyone [was] like me.”
As part of Lauren Laverne’s first Radio 4 Desert Island Discs show, he said he talked about the issue of gay rights to give others “hope.”
He also said that becoming a parent had made him less interested in winning the Olympics.
The show’s regular presenter, Kirsty Young, took several months off because of her illness.
Appearing as a shipwreck on Laverne's first show, Daley said he felt "less than" any other children growing up because "it was not socially acceptable to love boys and girls."
He said, “Even today, these feelings of being inferior and different are the real things that have given me the power and strength to succeed.”
In order not to disappoint everyone when they finally learned the truth about his sexuality, he wanted to prove that he was “something,” he continued.
The double Olympic bronze medallist is now a renowned LGBT activist and took advantage of his participation this year at the Commonwealth Games in Australia to ask more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he was speaking out because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without ramifications and wanted to restore “hope” to others.
