In June, they became parents to a boy named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley claimed that "his whole perspective" had changed.
“If you asked me last year, I was only thinking about winning a gold medal,” he said.
“You know what, there are things that are more important than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.”
Her son is named after her father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 from brain cancer.
Daley said his father had not accepted that he was going to die and that one of the last things he asked him was if they already had their tickets for London 2012 because he wanted to be seated in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him, ‘Dad, you’re not going to be in the front row anymore,’” he said.
“I held him by the hand when he stopped breathing and it took him to stop breathing and die to finally recognize that he was not invincible,” he added.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won a bronze medal.
“It was all I’d dreamed of all my life – diving in front of a crowd at home at the Olympics, there’s nothing better,” he said.
