Germany's new warship still postponed
According to local media, the new German Navy frigate should have been put into service in 2014 to replace the aging warships dating from the Cold War, but it will not be in service until at least next year due to faulty systems and exponential spending.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, which cites a military spokesman, the commissioning of the “Rheinland-Pfalz”, the flagship of the new frigates of Baden-Württemberg, has been postponed to the first half of 2019.
The ship should have joined the Navy in 2014, but worrying post-delivery issues have undermined the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships the Navy commissioned in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is certain that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some stealth technologies, such as a radar signature, infrared and reduced acoustics.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for up to two years outside of home ports.
According to Die Zeit, however, the relentless delays mean that war-avant-garde ships – which should allow Germany to project its force overseas – will already be obsolete when they are put into service.
Last year, the cursed F125 frigate made headlines when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
The reasons for this return were little known, but the German media mentioned a number of “software and hardware flaws” that rendered the warship useless in case of deployment on a combat mission.
Software flaws were particularly significant as the Baden-Württemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, which is half of the crews of the old Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it appears that the ship is significantly overloaded, which decreases its performance and reduces the ability of the Navy to make future improvements.
The 7,000-ton “Rheinland-Pfalz” is estimated to weigh twice as much as similar-class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Beyond the failures of the computer system, the price of the project as a whole - including the training of the crew - also becomes a problem.
It is said to have reached the astronomical sum of 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion dollars), compared to 2.2 billion initially.
The problems associated with the new frigates are of particular importance in light of the recent warnings that Germany's naval strength is declining.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament’s defence committee, acknowledged earlier this year that the navy is in fact “short of ships capable of deploying.”
The official said the situation had produced a snowball effect over time, as the old ships were downgraded but no replacement ships were designated.
He regretted that none of the Baden-Württemberg class frigates could join the Navy.
The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research in an area of the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The study by researchers from the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and sopranos as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton at the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using handheld detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of the bats’ screams as well as the activities of the different species.
A habitat map and report will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal the most important areas of habitat for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work such as grassland creation and how best to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects the perch and results in the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-killing papers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by pet cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to spot insects and obstacles on their flight route.
Responsible for protecting more than 270 historic buildings, 38 large gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, perch inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization has also established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threave site in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, Domain Manager, says the site is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have an ideal spot for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the right habitat.
But there is still a lot to learn about bats, so the work we do here and in other places will help us better understand what bats need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of checking the presence of bats before proceeding with the maintenance of properties, because by unintentionally destroying a single maternity nest, it can cause the death of 400 females and small, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their perch.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and as far as many of our species are concerned, we don’t know what’s going on in their populations right now.”
