Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty if they buy a property in the UK
Foreign buyers will have to pay higher stamp duty if they buy a property in the UK and the extra money will be used to help the homeless under the new conservative regimes.
This measure will nullify the success of Corbyn’s campaign to attract young voters
Stamp duty will be taxed on those who do not pay tax in the UK
The Treasury expects to raise up to 120 million pounds a year to help the homeless.
Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty rate if they buy a property in the UK - the extra money will be used to help the homeless, Theresa May will announce today.
This measure will be seen as an initiative to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn’s campaign to attract young voters by committing to providing more affordable housing and targeting high-income earners.
The increase in the stamp duty will be imposed on individuals and businesses that do not pay taxes in the UK, and the additional money will be used to strengthen the government’s efforts in the fight to help the homeless.
This surtax - in addition to the current stamp duty, including the higher levels introduced two years ago on second homes and rental purchases - could reach 3%.
The Treasury expects the project to raise up to 120 million pounds a year.
Approximately 13% of new construction in London is purchased by non-residents in the UK, which drives up prices and prevents first-time homeowners from gaining a foothold in the housing market.
Many rich areas of the country – especially in the capital – have become “ghost cities” because of the high number of foreign buyers who stay most of the time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson demanded a reduction in the stamp duty to help more young people buy a first home.
Accusing major construction companies of keeping real estate prices at a high level by seizing land without using it, he urged Ms. May to give up quotas on affordable housing in order to settle the “real estate disgrace” raging in the UK.
Mr. Corbyn presented an attractive set of reform proposals in the housing sector, including rent control and the elimination of “faultless” evictions.
He also wants to give councils more powers to build new housing.
Ms May said: “Last year, I said that I would dedicate my position as prime minister to the rebirth of the British dream – that every new generation would have a better life.
