Red Tide Info Point: Lower concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in some areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - causing fears of falling concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee County.
Islanders are found about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but at fewer sites than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County have been reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or off, medium concentrations in Charlotte County, and low concentrations in the Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported in northwest Florida in the past week.
